T2  - NUTRITION REPORTS INTERNATIONAL
LA  - English
AB  - The effects of dietary lactose on the levels or activities of selected biochemical parameters were investigated. In a 4-week feeding trial, weanling rats were fed semi-defined diets that were constituted to resemble dried milk except that lactose was varied from 0 to 50% w/w. Glucose was used to equalize the final carbohydrate levels. The lipid source was butter. The final 4-week values of the specific activities of lactase and invertase in gastrointestinal (GI) mucosal extracts and blood serum alkaline phosphatase (AP) were not significantly dependent on dietary lactose level. Serum cholesterol was significantly directly and triglyceride was significantly inversely dependent on the dietary lactose level. The cholesterol/triglyceride ratio increased significantly with increase in lactose level. Serum calcium levels were significantly inversely dependent on lactose level. Intestinal AP activity significantly decreased with increase in lactose level. The maximum extents of the  significant changes were: intestinal AP (-35%); serum cholesterol (+40%); serum triglyceride (-46%); serum calcium (-20%).
