AB  - Introduction: The aim of this study was to assess the relationships between blood glucose level, glycosylated haemoglobin (HbA1c), and bone mineral density (BMD) in patients with type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM).
   Method: 96 patients with T2DM were allocated to the diabetes group, and 72 patients with normal glucose tolerance to the control group. BMD, fasting plasma glucose (FPG), and HbA1c were measured accordingly. Diabetes patients with FPG <= 7.0 mmol/l were sub-allocated to the diabetes I group, and those with > 7.0 mmol/l to the diabetes II group. Gender, age, body mass index (BMI), HbA1c, HDL-C, TG, LDL-C, FPG, serum calcium (Ca), serum phosphorus (P), alkaline phosphatase (AKP), serum insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1), and BMD were recorded, and correlations between these indicators and the occurrence of -osteoporosis were explored.
   Results: FPG and HbA1c levels were significantly higher in the diabetes I and II groups than in the control group (p < 0.05). The BMDs in the lumbar spine and femoral neck were significantly higher in the control group than in the diabetes I and II groups (p < 0.05). FPG and HbA1c levels were higher in diabetes group II than in group I (p < 0.05). Single-factor analysis revealed significant differences in BMI, age, course of disease, waist-to-hip ratio, tea and milk consumption, IGF-1, and HbA(1c) levels (p < 0.05). Logistic regression analysis showed that the course of disease, gender, age, tea consumption, waist-to-hip ratio, HbA1c, and IGF-1 were primary risk factors for decreasing BMD in T2DM patients (p < 0.05).
   Conclusion: Decreased BMD in T2DM patients increases the risk of fractures. Poor control of blood glucose levels reduces BMD.
