LA  - English
AB  - Serum chemistries of a group of captive/crippled brown pelicans (Pelecanus occidentalis) were measured at monthly intervals for 14 months using a sequential multiple analyzer. Serum components related to bone and fat metabolism decreased with age until about 24 months old. Protein- and fat-related serum components were elevated between December and May, approximately coinciding with the breeding season of the captive birds and the winter-spring season of the geograpic region. Wild brown pelicans showed reduced serum cholesterol and glucose, relative to captives. Wild birds and captives maintained on sea-water had higher serum electrolytes than captives maintained on fresh water. Captive, egg-laying females had elevated levels of serum calcium, inorganic phosphorus and triglycerides relative to non-breeding females.
