TI  - EFFECTS OF 2 NEW DIETARY FIBER SUPPLEMENTS IN HEALTHY-VOLUNTEERS ON A WESTERN DIET
T2  - NUTRITION REPORTS INTERNATIONAL
LA  - English
AB  - The use of fiber supplements to increase fiber intakes of healthy subjects on low fiber diets will be feasible if beneficial effects of such supplements can be demonstrated in these subjects. We increased fiber intakes of healthy volunteers, randomized into a control and two experimental groups of 9 each, between 23.6 to 70%, by supplementing their habitual Western diets with a mineralized multifiber powder or a maize fiber tablet. Acceptability, and effects on body weight index, defecation  frequency, glucose tolerance, serum lipids, plasma fibrinogen, blood clotting time, serum calcium and magnesium and plasma pyridoxal-5''-phosphate and pyridoxal were determined after two and four weeks. Both supplements lowered serum cholesterol and triacylglyceroles in subjects with raised values and increased percentage HDL-cholesterol. Effects were significant for maize fiber, which also significantly decreased body weight index. We conclude that both supplements are suitable to increase  fiber intakes of healthy subjects.
