TI  - COMPARISONS OF PHARMACOLOGIC DOSAGES OF ACTH AND CORTISONE - ENDOCRINE AND BIOCHEMICAL INDICES
T2  - METABOLISM-CLINICAL AND EXPERIMENTAL
LA  - English
AB  - ACTH (200 units of gel intramuscularly) or hydrocortisone 100 mg.q.8 hr. per os) were administered daily to healthy adult males. Each produced the same mean increase in urinary 11-oxysteroids measured as Porter-Silber chromogens. ACTH had a greater effect in accentuating hyperglycemia during oral glucose tolerance tests. Both ACTH and hydrocortisone interfered to a comparable degree with the hypoglycemic action of insulin. ACTH evoked a much greater rise in urinary 17-ketosteroids. Urinary gonadotropins varied, but no consistent pattern of change was discerned. Urinary pressor amines were unaffected by either ACTH or hydrocortisone. Both ACTH and hydrocortisone lowered the serum potassium and raised the serum sodium levels, but the hypokalemia and hypernatremia were greater with ACTH. Serum CO2 increased equally with ACTH and hydrocortisone, and serum total proteins, albumin, and globulins decreased to the same degree with ACTH and hydrocortisone. Serum calcium levels decreased only during ACTH administration. The decrease in serum protein-bound iodine and total cholesterol, phos-pholipids and triglycerides, and in the beta lipoprotein fractions of the latter three constituents, was greater after ACTH. These beta lipoprotein changes occurred despite the fact that secretion of androgenic precursors of 17-ketosteroids, which increase these lipid fractions, presumably increased with ACTH.
