AB  - The onset of breeding season in many sub-mammalian vertebrates is correlated with an alteration in the composition of blood. In Acrohordus granulatus blood parameters such as plasma lipids, plasma cholesterol, plasma proteins and serum calcium greatly increase during the breeding period (i.e. during late December to early January); come to basal level and remain normal throughout nonbreeding period (i.e. during late January to early November). It is suggested that the rise in these blood parameters is due to the secretion of the ovarian estrogens, since only steroids are able to bring about such effect.
