AB  - Background: Recent studies have shown that endothelium function is impaired in end-stage renal failure and after renal transplantation, Apart from high blood pressure and uremic toxic effects, hyperparathyroidism may be an important cause for the impairment of endothelium function. Subjects and methods: The role of calcium phosphate metabolism on flow-mediated vasodilation as an index of endothelial function was studied in 40 normotensive renal transplant recipients (age 50 +/- 2 years, blood pressure 139 +/- 2/83 +/- 1 mmHg, serum creatinine 1.30 +/- 0.07 mg/dl, mean +/- SEM). After blood sampling to determine intact parathyroid hormone levels (iPT1195 +/- 12 ng/l, range 10 - 158 ng/l) and serum calcium and phosphate levels, flow-mediated vasodilation of the brachial artery (FMD) was investigated. Enddiastolic diameter and blood flow of the brachial artery were registered using a multigate Doppler system before, during, and 1, 3, 5, 7, and 10 minutes after forearm occlusion for 3 minutes. Nitroglycerin-induced (endothelium-independent) vasodilation (FND) was also measured. Results: FMD was 4.37 +/-1.09%, FND 19.3 +/- 1.4%. There was a significant inverse relationship between FMD and iPTH levels (r = -0.39, p = 0.014), but not between FMD und serum calcium (r = 0.02, p = 0.94) or phosphate levels (r = -0.18, p = 0.23). No relationship was found between FND or enddiastolic diameter of the brachial artery and iPTH levels. In the multiple regression analysis, the relationship between iPTH and FMD (beta -0.32, p = 0.04) was independent of serum calcium (beta 0.15, p = 0.38), phosphate (beta 0.13, p = 0.45), creatinine (beta -0.12, p = 0.48), cholesterol level (beta 0.13 - 0.15, p = 0.76), mean arterial pressure (beta 0.06, p = 0.76), age (beta 0.10, p = 0.56), and time after transplantation (beta 0.13, p = 0.43). Conclusion: The data indicate that hyperparathyroidism can contribute to vascular endothelial dysfunction in renal transplant recipients.
