AB  - Rats maintained on an atherogenic diet containing 0.5% cholesterol for 16 weeks show increased alkaline phosphatase activity and higher levels of serum inorganic P and Ca content of aorta. Administration of vitamin B12 and hydrolysed glucose cycloacetoacetate to the rats receiving cholesterol diet results in a progressive reduction in alkaline phosphatase activity, and of inorganic P level of serum and Ca content of aorta. It is suggested that high serum alkaline phosphatase activity in cholesterol-fed animals induces calcification by increasing the inorganic P level in serum resulting in the formation of Ca-P salt which gets deposited in the vascular tissue.
