TI  - BLOOD AND HEMODYNAMIC CHANGES IN DOGS FOLLOWING HEMORRHAGIC HYPOTENSION AND ITS TREATMENT WITH DEXTRAN
T2  - JOURNAL OF PHARMACOLOGY AND EXPERIMENTAL THERAPEUTICS
LA  - English
AB  - Blood chemistry and hematology studies, together with blood pressure, heart and respiratory rates, were carried out on dogs which were hemorrhaged to a blood pressure of 50 mm Hg and then transfused with an equal volume of dextran. Pyruvic and lactic acid values rose following hemorrhage, but fell on transfusion with dextran. The fall may be due to dilution, improved capillary flow, or both. Blood sugar followed a similar pattern. Dextran, by improving the circulation, may have increased the utilization of sugar. When the blood pressure was reduced to 50 mm Hg by bleeding, the injection of dextran, by increasing the plasma volume, raised the blood pressure to near normal. The elevated heart and respiratory rates resulting from hemorrhage fell on injection of dextran; this was probably the result of improved circulation and oxygena-tion. Following the injection of dextran, there was a fall in the hemato-crit, blood cholesterol, serum calcium, hemoglobin, RBC and WBC count, and rectal temperature, while the sedimentation rate rose. In general, the response of the blood components to dextran infusion could be due to the expected decrease in concentration when the blood volume is increased. All of the dogs which were hemorrhaged and not transfused with dextran died, while those which received dextran lived.
