TI  - TOTAL PROTEIN, CHOLESTEROL, MINERALS AND TRANSAMINASES IN PLASMA DURING PREPARTURIENT PERIOD IN GOATS
T2  - INDIAN JOURNAL OF ANIMAL SCIENCES
LA  - English
AB  - Variations in the concentrations of total protein, cholesterol, calcium and phosphorus and activities of glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase (GOT) and glutamic pyruvic transaminase (GPT) in plasma were studied during periparturient period in 10 Black Bengal-Beetal crossbred goats carrying single (3) and twin foetuses CI). Plasma total protein showed steep rise at 12 hr antepartum followed by a peak at kidding. Elevated cholesterol content during antepartum period showed a precipitous fall at kidding. Decreasing vend in plasma total protein and cholesterol was observed after kidding. Plasma total protein was significantly (P<0.05) higher in single than in twin pregnancy at 72 hr antepartum. Circulatory GOT and GPT activities indicated a rising pattern from 72 hr antepartum untill kidding, followed by a decreasing vend after kidding. A consistent pattern was noticed in plasma calcium and phosphorus levels during periparturient period. Nonsignificant differences were recorded in plasma cholesterol, calcium and phosphorus content, and in the activities of transaminases between goats bearing single and twin foetuses during periparturient period.
