TI  - ALTERATIONS IN SERUM CHEMISTRY OF BUFFALO FETUS DURING PRENATAL DEVELOPMENT
T2  - INDIAN JOURNAL OF ANIMAL SCIENCES
LA  - English
AB  - The biochemical analysis of serum of buffalo foetus beginning from the fifth month of gestational age was studied in 39 buffalo foetus. The serum calcium level decreased at the sixth and seventh months, but increased thereafter. Serum inorganic phosphorus increased at the sixth month and decreased to a minimum value at the eighth and tenth months. Serum magnesium decreased gradually till the seventh month, then began to increase at the eighth month, and decreased till parturition. Total serum bilirubin decreased from the sixth month till the period near parturition. Serum cholesterol gradually decreased to the minimum value at the eighth, and then again increased at the ninth and tenth months of gestation. The total protein concentration increased progressively from the fifth to the tenth month of gestation with a prominent increase in albumin near term. The electrophoretic pattern obtained showed 5 serum protein fractions, vis. pre-albumin, albumin, alphafetoprotein, beta-globulin  and gamma-globulin.
