TI  - SEASONAL-CHANGES IN PHYSIOLOGICAL-PARAMETERS OF WHITE-TAILED DEER IN OKLAHOMA
T2  - JOURNAL OF WILDLIFE MANAGEMENT
LA  - English
AB  - We evaluated seasonal changes in physiological parameters of 55 female white-tailed deer (Odocoileus virginianus) collected during 1985-86 (yr 1) and 1986-87 (yr 2) in south-central Oklahoma. Eviscerated carcass weight (ECW) and serum levels of glucose, triglycerides, non-esterified fatty acids (NEFA), thyroxine (T4), urea nitrogen (SUN), and phosphorus (P) were not different among seasons during either year. Kidney fat index (KFI) was highest (P .ltoreq. 0.049) in winter during year 1, and in fall and winter (P .ltoreq. 0.014) during year 2. Packed cell volume (PCV) was lower in summer (P .ltoreq. 0.041) than in fall and winter during year 2. Summer serum total protein (STP) levels were lower (P .ltoreq. 0.022) than fall and spring levels during year 1. Serum triiodothyronine (T3) was highest (P .ltoreq. 0.010) in fall during year 1. Serum sodium (Na) was highest (P .ltoreq. 0.045) in winter during year 1, and serum calcium (Ca) levels were higher (P .ltoreq. 0.011) in spring than in summer and fall during year 1. Potassium (K) was highest in summer (P .ltoreq. 0.010), and in spring and summer (P .ltoreq. 0.029) during years 1 and 2, respectively. Ruminal ammonia levels were lowest (P .ltoreq. 0.001) in summer during year 1. Total volatile fatty acid (TVFA) and acetate levels were highest (P .ltoreq. 0.038) in spring during year 1; summer levels were higher (P .ltoreq. 0.036) than fall and winter levels during year 2. The rumen acetate/propionate ratio (A/P) was lower (P .ltoreq. 0.026) in winter than in summer during both years. Seasonal trends in many variables examined suggested that deer nutritional status declined from winter through summer. Managers in the cross-timbers region should focus habitat improvement efforts in spring and summer.
