AB  - Weekly clinical and laboratory examinations were carried out on 39 holstein-friesian cows of a farm 3 weeks before and 5 weeks after calving. During this period, left displacement of the abomasum (DPA) developed in 7 animals. Of the laboratory changes characteristic for DPA, metabolic alcalosis of the blood was found in 3 cows (43%), hypochloremia in 5 cows (71%) and increased ruminal chloride values in 6 cows (86%) even 1 to 2 weeks preceding the clinical manifestation of DPA. Hypopotassemia was observed only in 3 animals (43%) at the time of the clinical manifestation of DPA. Of the frequently observed "intercurrent diseases", hypocalcemia was observed in a single case at the time of the clinical manifestation of DPA. Results of blood plasma and milk examinations indicated subclinical ketosis in 6 cows, in 5 animals (71%) at least one week before the clinical manifestation of DPA (Table). At this time, low blood sugar levels were found, while during the least stage of DPA, hyperglucemia was frequently observed. Increased blood plasma-total bilirubin, SDH and total lipid values, characteristic for liver injury, were found in 4 cows, of them in three cases (43%) even before the clinical manifestation of DPA (table). The following mean values of affected and normal cows without DPA showed significant differences, in some instances at different points of time: blood: pH, pCO2, act.- .**GRAPHIC**. blood plasma: Cl-, K+, total cholesterol, AST, SDH, glucose; rumen juice: chloride total acidity. Significant differences were not found in the values of Ca, Mg2+, anorg. P, pH of rumen juice, pH of urine, as well as of net acid-base excretion. At a stock level, determination of chloride level in the blood plasma and rumen juice may promote the early diagnosis of DPA during the so-called "metabolic profile" examinations. For the individual diagnosis, percussion and auscultory examinations are more favourable. The results obtained indicated the secondary character  of hypocalcaemia. Further investigations are required to clear up the possible role of ketosis and liver injury (lipid mobilizational disease) in the pathogenesis that may be supposed in certain cases.
