AB  - In a large-scale dairy farm, of 729 cows, 43 showed displacement of abomasum (DA). The frequency of left and right DA was 90.7% and 9.3%, respectively. The disease developed in 11.5% of 388 holstein-friesian cows while only 0.7% of 599 crossed cows with lower milk yield were affected. Metabolic alkalosis was found in 69% of investigated cows that was frequently accompanied with hypochloraemia and/or hypopotassaemia. In the examined samples, hypo- or hypercalcemia, hypo- or hyperphosphataemia were found in 30%, 9%, 40% and 10%, respectively. Hypoglycaemia was found in 15% of cows, while hyperglycaemia in 50%. By the Ross test, ketonaemia, ketonuria and ketolactia were found in 52%, 63% and 40% of all the investigated cases, respectively. Chloride ionic concentration of rumen juice (.hivin.x = 50.2 .+-. s = 23.8 mmol/l) was higher than the physiologic level (30 mmol/l) in 85% of affected cows. 43% of affected cows showed (mostly so-called "paradox") aciduria: pH .ltoreq. 7.4, netto  acid-base excretion (NAB-E) .ltoreq. 0 mmol/l. This was followed only partially by hypopotassaemia, as well as by hypochloraemia, mentioned in the literature. Significant, negative correlation was found (p < 0.05) between the Ca++ level and act. -HCO3-, and BE values of blood, as well as Cl- content of rumen juice. Significant differences were found between the mean values of blood pH, pCO2, act. -HCO3-, and BE values, the Ca++, anorg. P, K+, Cl-, total cholesterol, total bilirubin and glucose content of blood plasma, as well as between the Cl- level of rumen juice and pH and NAB-E concentration of urine of affected and control cows (Tables 1 and 2). For the laboratory diagnosis of the disease, the Cl- determination of blood plasma and rumen juice is proposed.
