TI  - EFFECT OF CHRONIC HYPERCALCEMIA ON THE HEART - AN ANALYSIS OF 18 NECROPSY PATIENTS
T2  - AMERICAN JOURNAL OF MEDICINE
LA  - English
AB  - Certain clinical and morphologic cardiac observations are described in 18 necropsy patients, 33-58 yr old (mean 45 yr) (14 women), with chronic hypercalcemia (11.6-34.4 mg/dl [19.4]) from 1-9 yr (mean 5 yr). Primary hyperparathyroidism was present in 9 patients and secondary hyperparathyroidism in the other 9 (of renal origin in 7). Cardiac valve anular and coronary arterial calcific deposits were present in 10 patients (group I) including 4 (mean age 51 yr) with considerable narrowing of 2 or 3 of the 4 major epicardial coronary arteries. None of the other 8 patients (group II) had cardiac valve anular or cuspal calcific deposits; only 2 had coronary calcific deposits, small in each, and none had significant coronary luminal narrowing. Ca was in the media (medial calcinosis) with or without intimal deposition, of the coronary arteries in 5 patients. Comparison of the patients in group I to those in group II disclosed similar mean ages, durations of hypercalcemia and serum Ca levels, but significantly (P < 0.05) higher mean total serum cholesterol levels (216 vs. 163 mg/dl) and heart weights (426 vs. 320 g). Chronic hypercalcemia is associated with accelerated deposition of Ca in the cardiac anuli and valvular cusps, in the media and intima of the coronary arteries and in individual myocardial fibers (dystrophic calcification). Coronary intimal calcification may be associated with or produce luminal narrowing, especially in patients with serum total cholesterol levels > 200 mg/dl. Chronic hypercalcemia may be viewed as a risk factor to accelerated coronary atherosclerosis.
