TI  - BIOCHEMICAL CONSEQUENCES OF HYDROCHLOROTHIAZIDE THERAPY FOR ESSENTIAL-HYPERTENSION
T2  - CURRENT THERAPEUTIC RESEARCH-CLINICAL AND EXPERIMENTAL
LA  - English
AB  - The biochemical effects of hydrochlorothiazide (HCTZ) therapy were analyzed in 257 hypertensive patients who received HCTZ (25 to 75 mg TID) for up to six months. Although the effects observed were those commonly associated with diuretics, several interesting observations were made. A decrease in mean sodium level and an increase in cholesterol concentration were transient, seen only at the one-month evaluation, and mean fasting glucose level was not significantly elevated until after three months of therapy. There were no statistically significant relationships between sex, age, or dose of HCTZ and observed changes in the results of the laboratory tests studied. A greater decrease (P < 0.01) in mean serum potassium concentrations were observed in white patients than in black patients (-0.7 vs -0.3 mEq/L at one month). While no change in serum calcium concentrations was observed in white patients, there was a significant (P < 0.01) increase in calcium levels in black patients. The availability of other antihypertensive agents that are not associated with the biochemical consequences of HCTZ therapy suggests the need to reassess the use of diuretics as initial monotherapy of hypertension.
