TI  - PATHOGENESIS OF EXPERIMENTAL LEPTOSPIRA-INTERROGANS, SEROVAR BATAVIAE, INFECTION IN DOG - MICROBIOLOGICAL, CLINICAL, HEMATOLOGIC, AND BIOCHEMICAL STUDIES
T2  - AMERICAN JOURNAL OF VETERINARY RESEARCH
LA  - English
AB  - Beagles experimentally infected with L. interrogans serovar bataviae, strain 1415, developed a spectrum of disease that ranged from mild to fatal in severity. Hepatic, renal and hemorrhagic signs dominanted the clinical presentation and supported the polysystemic nature of leptospiral infection. All the dogs were leptospiremic from postinoculation (PI) h 24-120. Leptospiruria persisted from PI h 72 to PI wk 4. Serum agglutinins occurred by PI day 10, reached peak titers at about PI mo. 1 and persisted up to PI mo. 5. Severe or moderate disease was characterized by a mild anemia, severe leukocytosis and thrombocytopenia and a marked increase in erythrocyte sedimentation rate and plasma fibrinogen, but prothrombin times and partial thromboplastin times were unaltered. Increases in serum of alkaline phosphatase, aspartate aminotransferase, total, conjugated and free bilirubin, cholesterol, lactic dehydrogenase, alanine aminotransferase, and amylase and changes in protein electrophoresis were indicative of both hepatic and other organ system pathologic findings. Increases of serum urea N and creatinine, hyponatremia, hypochloremia, hypokalemia, hyperphosphatemia and mild hypocalcemia, as well as reductions in serum CO2 and blood pH, were seen in the severely affected dogs. The clinical and pathologic manifestations paralleled those of human leptospirosis. Thus L. interrogans bataviae leptospirosis in dogs may provide a large laboratory animal model for the study of human leptospirosis.
