TI  - LATE COMPLICATIONS OF LONG-TERM HEMODIALYSIS IN CHILDREN - CLINICAL ASPECTS AND SOME MEASURABLE VARIABLES CONCERNING PARATHYROID-HORMONE, DIVALENT IONS, ACID-BASE METABOLISM, ANEMIA, NUTRITION, GROWTH AND SURVIVAL DATA
T2  - JOURNAL OF UROLOGY
LA  - English
AB  - Pediatric patients (19) ranging in age from 5-17 yr, were followed for up to 59 mo. and 3129 hemodialysis procedures were done. The known duration of renal diseases before hemodialysis was 6 .+-. 3 yr. The clinical complications consisted of 5 patients with sepsis, 2 patients with malignant hypertension, 6 patients with congestive heart failure, 3 patients with seizure disorders and 1 patient with intractable ascites. Radiologic evidence for renal osteodystrophy was present in 4 patients, although elevated levels of parathyroid hormone were documented in all patients after 6 mo. of hemodialysis. Hypocalcemia (8.4 .+-. 1.7 mg/dl) was documented before initiation of hemodialysis and normalization occurred in only 1/2 of the patients after 6 mo. of hemodialysis with the dialysate Ca concentration of 3 meq/l. Pre-dialysis serum concentrations for Mg (2.5 .+-. 0.4 mg/dl), phosphorus (5.3 .+-. 1.5 mg/dl), triglyceride (138 .+-. 31 mg/dl), cholesterol (180 .+-. 34 mg/dl) and total protein (6.6 .+-. 0.6 gm/dl) were normal. Elevated values were found for hydroxyproline (19.6 .+-. 2.9 .mu.g/dl) and uric acid (9.3 .+-. 1.5 mg/dl). Metabolic acidosis (total CO2 < 20 mEq/l) was present in 50% of the patients and corrected only in 1/2 of these after hemodialysis. The mean hematocrit concentration was 13.8 .+-. 2.0%. A 50% reduction in serum creatinine (10 .+-. 2 to 5 .+-. 2 mg/dl) and urea (101 .+-. 29 to 50 .+-. 27 mg/dl) was achieved after 4 to 5 h of hemodialysis. The dietary intakes of 1000 .+-. 400 calories per m2 per day and 1.3 .+-. g/kg per day of protein were 50 and 90% that of recommended allowances. Height measurements under the 3rd percentile of normal were noted in 62% of the children. The actuarial survival data showed a mean survival at 2 yr of 75%.
