TI  - EXPERIMENTAL HUMAN MAGNESIUM DEPLETION .I. CLINICAL OBSERVATIONS + BLOOD CHEMISTRY ALTERNATIONS
T2  - AMERICAN JOURNAL OF CLINICAL NUTRITION
LA  - English
AB  - Clinical and chemical changes are reported which occurred in the course of a longterm study on the effect of feeding a purified Mg-deficient diet by tube to 2 elderly male subjects. Neither had significant gastrointestinal, renal, endocrine or other disease which might modify Mg or other nutritional requirements. In the initial depletion studies, plasma Mg levels fell slowly but progressively for several months to levels approximately one-third to one-fourth the control levels and then stabilized. Red cell Mg levels fell more slowly and after 3 months were two-thirds of normal. In 1 subject symptoms and signs occurred after approximately 100 days of depletion. These included personality changes, symptoms of gastrointestinal disturbance, gross tremor, fasciculations and hyporeflexia in the presence of positive Trousseau and Chvostek signs. These reverted to normal following the administration of Mg salts and did not recur with continuation of the supplemented diet for another 5 months. In the second subject signs of paralytic ileus developed after 55 days of depletion in the first study, but only electromyographic changes in the second study which lasted for a period of 38 weeks. Despite an adequate Ca intake, serum Ca levels fell markedly in both subjects as the hypomagnesemia persisted. Hypokalemia developed and large additional intakes of K were required for maintenance of serum levels; this was correlated with decreased total exchangeable K. In both subjects, serum Ca levels returned to normal following Mg repletion, and serum K levels rose. In view of the hypocalcemia accompanying hypomagnesemia in these subjects and the dramatic improvement with Mg repletion, it is suggested that these 2 ions, and K, are intimately related in their metabolism. Serial data on serum P, uric acid, cholesterol and proteins are presented. When supplemented with Mg and adequate absorbable Fe, the purified diet utilized in this study is capable of maintaining weight and good general health over a prolonged period.
