TI  - ENHANCED RECTAL ABSORPTION OF [ASU1,7]-EEL CALCITONIN IN RATS USING POLYACRYLIC-ACID AQUEOUS GEL BASE
T2  - JOURNAL OF PHARMACEUTICAL SCIENCES
LA  - English
AB  - The effects of polyacrylic acid aqueous gel on the absorption of rectally administered [Asu1,7]-eel calcitonin, a calcitonin analog, were investigated in rats. The [Asu1,7]-eel calcitonin (1 U/kg) was given into the rectal loop in gel bases at various pH (5.5-8.5) and polyacrylic acid concentrations (0.01-1.0% w/v [wt/vol]). The maximum hypocalcemic effect was obtained in .apprx. 30 min after administration of the analog in a 0.1% w/v polyacrylic acid gel base at pH 5.5. The plasma Ca  level decreased by .apprx. 18% from the initial level. Rectal administration in vehicles such as polyethylene glycol 1000, triglyceride fatty acid mixture base or saline solution had little or no hypocalcemic effect at a dose of 5 U/kg. Evidently a polyacrylic acid aqueous gel base significantly improved the absorption of this analog. Rectal administration in a polyacrylic acid gel base (0.1% w/v; pH 5.5) required a dose 35 times greater than an i.v. administered dose to achieve an equivalent  hypocalcemic effect. [Calcitonin, a hypocalcemic peptide hormone, has been isolated from the thyroid of mammals and ultimobranchials and has been used for the treatment of Paget''s disease as well as certain types of osteoporosis.].
