AB  - Bacground Calcium and cholestrol play major roles in the formation of atherosclerosis. Whether severe atherosclerosis induced by co-administration of a mixture containing vitamin D-2 (vit D-2) and cholestrol can result in gastric hemorrhagic damage is unknown. Gastric oxidative stress and hemorrhagic ulceration in rats with atherosvlerosis induced by co-administration of vit D-2 and cholestrol and the protective effect of lysozyme chloride on this ulcer model were investigated.
   Material/Methods Male Wistar rats were challenged once daily for 9 days with 1.0ml/kg of corn iol containing vit D-2 and cholestrol to induce atherosclerosis. Contorl rats received the same volume of cron oil only. After 24-h fasting followed by fgastric surgery, the rat stomachs were irrigated for 3 h with stimulated rat gastric juice or normal saline. Various gastric mucosal ulcergenic factors (acid back-diffusion, lipid peroxides, histamine concentration, and hemorrhagic ulcers) and defensive substances (mucosal glutathione and mucus secretion) were determined.
   Results Augmentation of serum calcium concentration, total cholestrol, and low-density lipoprotein was observed in atherosclerotic rats. Grater mucosal ulcerogenic parameters and lower defensive substances were achieved in these rats. Daily intragastric lysozyme cholride dose-dependently protected gastric mucosal hemorrhagic damage in the atherosclerotic rats.
   Conclusions Atherosclerosis induced by co-administration of vit D-2 and cholestrol could produce gastric oxidative stress and hemorrhagic ulcer that was ameliorated lysozyme chloride in rats.
