TI  - INHIBITORY EFFECTS OF ACETYLATED THYROTROPIN ON METASTATIC THYROID CANCER
T2  - CANCER
LA  - English
AB  - An attempt has been made to evaluate the influence of the pituitary on thyroid cancer by the administration of a thyrotropin inhibitor, acetyl thyrotropin (TSH), to 9 patients with follicular and alveolar carcinoma of the thyroid. In 3 of 4 patients with palpable tumor masses there was a decrease in size or hardness of the metastases during the administration of acetyl TSH. In 3 patients there was a decrease in urinary calcium. The hypercalcemia in 1 patient disappeared with therapy. Osteogenic activity was stimulated on the basis of increased serum alkaline phosphatase in 4 patients without change in liver function. Thyroid function decreased in all patients during acetyl TSH treatment. In 7 patients there was a fall in protein-bound iodine. There was a significant decrease in basal metabolic rate in 1 patient and a suggestive decrease in 2 other patients. Radioactive iodine studies revealed inhibition of neck uptake or body retention of the isotope in 6 patients. The serum cholesterol increased in 1 patient and decreased in 6 patients treated with acetyl TSH. On the basis of these studies it is concluded that pituitary TSH is important for the growth and function of metastatic thyroid cancer.
